  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering in several key ways:\n\n1. Global Anti-Money Laundering Standards\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) recommendations\n- Establish minimum standards for national regulations\n- Provide framework for combating financial crimes\n\n2. International Cooperation Mechanisms\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Coordinated investigations across jurisdictions\n\n3. Regulatory Compliance Requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Cross-border financial transparency requirements\n\n4. Legal Enforcement Frameworks\n- Extradition agreements\n- Seizure and forfeiture of illicit assets\n- Prosecution of transnational financial crimes\n\n5. International Financial Systems\n- Banking regulations\n- Correspondent banking oversight\n- International payment network monitoring\n\n6. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Provide legal foundations for international cooperation\n- Establish common definitions and approaches\n\n7. Bilateral and Multilateral Agreements\n- Specific legal frameworks between countries\n- Detailed protocols for financial crime investigation\n\nThese intersections create complex, evolving legal landscapes for addressing money laundering globally.",
